website_summaries.verdict: The best way to sample a variety of healthy wet food flavors.
pros: Variety pack sits at a low price point, making it ideal for sampling a range of flavors
Plastic containers are easy to store in the fridge so you can serve half of the food at a time
Saucy, real meat chunks mix well with dry food
cons: You may need to cut them up for small dogs

customer_reviews.title: Made in China & hardly anything in the container
customer_reviews.text: Evidently it tasted good because he gobbles it down fast. But the poor little guy wasn't getting hardly any solid food, so was frantic for more all the time. It would be safe to say that there was NO MORE than 1 tablespoon of actual food in each cup and the rest was a thin broth. Then, I found out it was made in China! No wonder! Tonight he threw it all up after eating his dinner. Will never buy Rachel Ray brands again, ever!! I found another brand, made in USA, in the same size container, but is listed as "pottage style", meaning a thick stew. Going to try it for our little guy.
customer_reviews.author: Tamara McCarty

customer_reviews.title: Dog will not go near his food bowl
customer_reviews.text: My dog loved these when I first purchased them. When the next order came, he wouldn't even walk by it. He HATES it now and I don't know why. Seems like they changed the recipe or something is in it all of a sudden they don't like at all. I know I am not the first reviewer to say this either. He will occasionally eat the duck one but will not have anything to do with the lamb. AND will not eat it 2 days in a row either.
customer_reviews.author: ds94ta

customer_reviews.title: Dogs Love It!
customer_reviews.text: I have two chihuahua's, one who is a fairly picky eater and they both love this food! We've tried each flavor and they seem to like them equally so this variety pack is great. In fact, it's so much like home cooking I tasted it myself and frankly, it's pretty much "people food" quality. We've also tried several of Rachael's dog treats and every single one has been very high quality and again, so much like people food I forget it's for the dogs!
customer_reviews.author: CB

customer_reviews.title: Did Not get eaten waste of money  $
customer_reviews.text: My dogs did not like it so, it is a waste of money for me unfortunately so No Value for my $ and I thought maybe even though it was pricy it would be healthy so worth the cost but No total waste and Now I'm stuck with it because it comes in a 2 pack. And all chicken flavor only :(
customer_reviews.author: CCB

customer_reviews.title: A hit and a miss
customer_reviews.text: The food itself is great. My dog loves it, and she eats it along with dry food in the same brand. My first order of the carton of 16 came without a hitch. This second one? I received one container, rather than one carton. Amazon refunded me, so the only worry is finding it in a local store, due to the time factor.
customer_reviews.author: Chell

customer_reviews.title: Yummy food, good price
customer_reviews.text: Rachel Ray is a high value food. It's nutritious, all natural, and is a good price. This beef and chicken combo in gravy is awesome to mix with my puppy's dry dog food (Blue Buffalo Wilderness red meat puppy formula). I give her half a cup of dry food and 1 of these 3.5 ounce cups twice a day. This came in perfect condition. It comes in the retail sleeves like you would see on the shelf at your local pet store. I'll buy this product again.
customer_reviews.author: Kenzie

customer_reviews.title: no buy. pesticide controversy in the air.

customer_reviews.title: Dogs love it

Susie-Q is a 7 year old Basenji/Jack Russell Terrier mix. She’s a bit heavy, and with this diet, she’s starting to lose weight very gradually. When she gets down to the proper weight, we will increase her food portion amount.

If these pieces of chicken weren’t sitting in a gravy bath, the dark would be even harder bites for an old chihuahua with very few teeth to chew. As it is she chokes occasionally, so I discontinued the subscription.
